---
import Links from '../components/Links'
import ReactGridComponent from '../components/ReactGrid/ReactGrid'
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro'
---

<Layout title="react-grid"
  ><h1>react-grid</h1>
  <Links
    links={{
      npm: 'https://www.npmjs.com/package/@silevis/reactgrid',
      github: 'https://github.com/silevis/reactgrid',
      docs: 'https://reactgrid.com/examples/?utm_source=github&utm_medium=readme',
    }}
  />

  <h2>Meeting the requirements:</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><b><u>Quite extensive documentation</u></b></li>
    <li><b>Virtualization:</b> Yes</li>
    <li><b>Large data sets:</b> Virtualization</li>
    <li><b>TypeScript:</b> Yes</li>
    <li style={{ color: 'red' }}><b>Merge cells:</b> No</li>
    <li><b>Text formatting:</b> Yes</li>
    <li><b>Custom elements:</b> Yes</li>
    <li><b>Cell selection + copy, paste, delete:</b> Yes</li>
    <li><b>Keyboard navigation:</b> Yes, highly developed</li>
    <li><b>Copy content as a table:</b> Yes</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    <b>Opinion: </b>Overall, at first glance, it seems quite decent to work
    with. Not amazing or even very goodâ€”just okay. It looks like something that
    can be customized to fit individual needs. It offers quite a few features
    provided by the developers.
  </p>

  <p style={{ color: 'red', textAlign: 'center' }}>
    <u
      >The app crashed when generating 1000x10,000 data so I left the data
      small. This is a hint that the library is not very well optimized for
      large data sets.</u>
  </p>

  <hr style={{ marginBlock: '2%' }} />

  <ReactGridComponent client:load /></Layout
>
